Dear Indian Express,
I'm sorry to write that your journalists are there to interpret events wrong and distorted display, just to make some sensational headlines. The news about the upcoming singer Nahid Afreen was prepared without proper research and investigation. It was very sad to see that your journalists do not even know the difference between fatwa and appeal.
A fatwa is a non-binding legal opinion that can only be issued by a qualified lawyer (mufti) at the request of someone who can not understand religious guidelines. The leaflet distributed as a fatwa is just a copy of a signed appeal from 46 men who believe in religious practices. The merit of the vocation can be discussed for many reasons and in many dimensions, but first and foremost an appeal can not be called a legal opinion (fatwa).
We expect an apology from you for such a mistake.

Do you know how safe it is to hear Azan in the morning? Thieves and evil doers run away, thinking that now the believers are on their way to the mosques.

Cow in Hinduism:

Eating beef (Cow Mata) is allowed in Hinduism.
Rigveda (10/85/13) explains: "On the occasion of a girl's wedding, oxen and cows are slaughtered."
Rigveda (6/17/1) states that "Indra ate the meat of cow, calf, horse and buffalo".
Manusmriti (chapter 5 / verse 30) says, "It is not sinful to eat meat from edible animals, for Brahma created both the eaters and the edible."
Maharishi Yagyavalkya says in Shatpath Brahman (3/1/2/21): "I eat beef because it is very soft and delicious."
Apastamb Grihsutram (1/3/10) says: "The cow should be slaughtered on the arrival of a guest on the occasion of the 'Shraddha' of the ancestors and on the occasion of a wedding."
Vashistha Dharmasutra (11/34) writes, "When a Brahmin refuses to eat the flesh offered to him on the occasion of 'Shraddha' or worship, he goes to hell."

What you should know about Turkish President Recap Tayyip Erdogan:

The Turkish economy between 2002 and 2012 caused 64% real GDP growth and 43% GDP per capita growth.

Erdoğan inherited a $ 23.5 billion debt to the IMF, which was reduced to $ 0.9 billion in 2012. He decided not to sign a new contract. Turkey's debt to the IMF was therefore declared fully paid and he announced that the IMF could borrow from Turkey.

In 2010, five-year sovereign credit default swaps hit a record low of 1.17%, below the levels of nine EU Member States and Russia.

In 2002, the Turkish central bank had reserves of $ 26.5 billion. This amount reached USD 92.2 billion in 2011. During the tour of Erdoğan. Inflation fell in 2004 from 32% to 9.0%.

Under Erdoğan's government, the number of airports in Turkey increased from 26 to 50.

Between 2002 and 2011, a further 13500 km of motorway were built.

High-speed lines were built for the first time in Turkey's history and the country's high-speed train was put into operation in 2009. In 8 years 1076 km of railway were built and 5449 km of railway line renewed.

Erdogan has invested more in the healthcare system than any predecessor. As part of the reforms, the Green Card program has been introduced, offering free health benefits to the poor.

Erdoğan increased spending on education from LR 7.5 billion in 2002 to LR 34 billion in 2011. The highest share of state budget in a ministry and the number of universities in Turkey almost doubled from 98 in 2002 to 186 in October 2012.
